CVE-2004-2761 "SSL Certificate Signed Using Weak Hashing Algorithm"
Firepower/FMC is not affected by this vulnerability because of below reason.
"SSL certificates are used in two places in the product:
for the web server and for the [SSL] tunnel connections between Sourcefire devices.
Web server - The default SSL keys that ship with the product for the web server use an MD5 hash.
However, this key is not signed by a trusted CA.
The customer can replace this certificate with their own that uses a stronger hash algorithm.
[SSL] tunnel connections - The tunnel connections also use SSL keys that are signed using MD5 hashes.
However, these certificates are signed by a CA that is internal to the DC and only this CA is trusted for authenticating the certificates.
Therefore, an attacker would not be able to spoof a valid certificate for these connections."

Customer Name:NATIONAL UNIVERSITY OF SINGAPORE Service  Request Number:688396261 FA case Number:FA-0423002 The Failure Analysis (FA) Case for parts described below has been closed. Fault Isolated Problem Reported: 
The customer reported: After replacing one server heartbeat timeout was reported between the primary and secondary units in cluster. 

Failure Analysis Investigation: 
On receipt of this FP8300-STACK-K9 (JMX1849809J) and FP8300-STACK-K9 (JMX2007805C), the failure data was reviewed and a visual inspection of the units was performed. Both units passed a visual inspection.

The customer's symptom was duplicated on both units. Both units powered on normally, however after each unit booted to OS, the boot log showed Stacking errors. The issue was isolated to the images on both units. Both units were re-imaged. Afterward both units booted to OS successfully and passed all diagnostic testing with no further issues.

Failure Analysis Conclusion: 
The fault was isolated to corrupted OS images on both units. This case is being closed as 'Fault isolated'.

ACTION TAKEN:
*   We discussed the objectives and the unexpected behavior witnessed.
*   Application server was stuck in initializing.
*   restarted the services , Application server came back.
*   no core dump generated.
This should be generated if high CPU caused the system crash.
*   George   confirmed that authentication latency was seen earlier along with high CPU:
?  Explained that as Core dump was not generated it is difficult to pinpoint which thread was hogging CPU  and caused the  High latency and  triggered Application server initializing.
?  In case the issue happens again we need to collect thread dump and heap dump from CLI for analysis:
?  We also need the output of "tech top " for identify the process causing high CPU.
Here's what @Aaron Sanabria Martinez (asanabri)<mailto:asanabri@cisco.com> troubleshooted regarding NTP after my shift ended:
You noticed that timezone was on UTC ,  the rest of the nodes in the deployment are in Singapore
But you did not complete the step as it will restart the applications server on the node.
Now we noticed that the primary node is having ntp server issues, ntp service is down, when we do #show NTP we get the following error: "506 Cannot talk to daemon." .
As  mentioned this issue is related to the following bug: CSCvw03693<https://bst.cloudapps.cisco.com/bugsearch/bug/CSCvw03693> which we confirmed by getting the following output from CLI:
hsdc-pan-nac01/admin# show logging system  messages | inc chronyd
2021-10-28T12:46:06.701968+00:00 hsdc-pan-nac01 chronyd[117365]: chronyd version 3.2 starting (+CMDMON +NTP +REFCLOCK +RTC +PRIVDROP +SCFILTER +SECHASH +SIGND +ASYNCDNS +IPV6 +DEBUG)
2021-10-28T12:46:06.703775+00:00 hsdc-pan-nac01 chronyd[117365]: Fatal error : Could not get chrony uid/gid
2021-10-28T12:46:06.704586+00:00 hsdc-pan-nac01 chronyd: Could not get chrony uid/gid
2021-10-28T12:46:06.717983+00:00 hsdc-pan-nac01 systemd: chronyd.service: control process exited, code=exited status=1
2021-10-28T12:46:06.725924+00:00 hsdc-pan-nac01 systemd: Failed to start NTP client/server.
Now the work around for is that is to create user chronyd was not created during the upgrade, so the work around will require us to gaint root access to the PAN and create that user and assign it to proper group, then we will restart the chronyd service.
During inter build from 2.6 to 2.7 or higher, post-osupgrade converts ntp to chrony, by removing ntp configs and creating chrony user.
At the point where post-osupgrade writes the change to running config, startupcfg loads /etc/passwd, /etc/shadow from storedconfig.
Hence, the user never gets created and we see ntp failures after upgrade.
ACTION PLAN:
*   Cisco TAC will login to Root shell and apply the workaround for CSCvw03693<https://bst.cloudapps.cisco.com/bugsearch/bug/CSCvw03693>
*   Timezone will be changed on PAN node to Singapore (this will cause Ise application services to restart)

Problem Details: Hello Support,

According to the documentation for the controller VMs, its stated that the memory reservation for my HX model HX240c-M5SX is 72GB.
However this is much too high in my opinion, as in my cluster, each ESXi node only has a total of 128GB of ram. That means that 56% of the available RAM is currently in use by this storage controller. I know that this memory is reserved to ensure that there will be no performance degradation/contesting of resource between production VMs and storage controllers. 

However, because the storage controller is using so much memory, I can only provision a handful of VMs. Because of this constraint, I highly doubt that performance will be affected if the memory is reduced for these controller VMs.

Is it possible to reduce  the memory reservation on the storage controller VMs? How do I go about doing so? Any performance impact that I'm not aware of?

Hello Baby John,
I have reviewed the logs collected by the scrip.
Please be advised that many of the CPU spikes recorded were not caused by the SNMP but by the SSH process.
During that times user”cw2k” has been connected to the device from "dale2.network.nus.edu.sg”
In terms of the CPU spikes that indeed were caused by “SNMP Engine” process, unfortunately the decode of the functions doesn’t point us to any specific OID.
In this case, as discussed yesterday, I suggest performing following actions:
1.
Keep the script in place, so that have timestamps on when the problem is caused by “SNMP Engine” process.
Alternatively you might want to configure CPU threshold notifications using: "process cpu threshold type total rising 80 interval 10 falling 40 interval 10”
2.
You might try configuring SNMP view and excluding few of the tables that are known to spike the CPU when polled.
You might want to try applying SNMP View similar to the following one:
********************************************
snmp-server view cutdown iso included
snmp-server view cutdown ciscoFlashMIB excluded
snmp-server view cutdown 1.3.6.1.2.1.4.21 excluded
snmp-server view cutdown 1.3.6.1.2.1.4.22 excluded
snmp-server view cutdown 1.3.6.1.2.1.3 excluded
snmp-server view cutdown dot1dTpFdbEntry excluded
!! and apply it to all of the community strings configured with commands similar to:
snmp-server community <write_community_string> view <any_word> RW
snmp-server community <read_community_string> view <any_word> RO
********************************************
3.
Consider running either “debug snmp packet” on affected switch or SPAN session capturing all SNMP traffic.
This information together with the timestamp captured in point (1) should help you determine which OIDs polled from the switch cause the spike.

Problem Details: DNAC - Radius server change for WLC (Cisco 8540 Wireless Controller) creates new WLAN ID on WLC, but doesn't change the auth/acct configuration of existing WLAN

Impacting WLC provisioning for radius change DNAC - Radius server change for WLC (Cisco 8540 Wireless Controller) creates new WLAN ID on WLC, but doesn't change the auth/acct configuration of existing WLAN

Impacting WLC provisioning for radius change timestamp : 2022-07-22T20:08:50.000+0000 || updatedby : jossprag || type : RESOLUTION SUMMARY || visibility : External || details : • Customer was able to successfully upgrade their lab DNAC to 2.2.2.9.
• After the upgrade, they provisioned the 5520 WLC and see if the WLANs were getting replaced or updated.
  • According to the config preview, audit logs, and the config comparison chart, the WLANs got replaced instead of getting edited.

• Myself, Jay, and Daisy explained to the customer again why that is happening.
  • The DNAC just got done upgrading, so there are bound to be config changes.
  • They made some changes at the site level, so the DNAC will be pushing configs from the site level, not at the global level.
  • They also made some changes on the Wireless page by pressing the "Configure AAA" button and selected the ISE server from the drop-down menu.

***** July 19th, 2022 *****
• Samir confirmed that upgrading the DNAC to 2.2.2.9, on their production DNAC, fixed the hundreds of line config changes that would be pushed to the WLC.
  • The DNAC is now updating/replacing if it needs to be updated/replaced and add new config if the config isn't on the WLC already.

• We explained how the naming system worked involving the profile name on the WLC.
  • The DEs of the WLC purposefully created a 32-character limit on the profile name of the WLANs.
    • There was issues in the past when the DEs tried to extend the character limit, so they changed it back to being just 32-characters.
• Customer will need to make sure that every site, building, and floor have unique characters, so that the profile name on the WLC GUI will be unique too.

• Customer gave permission to close the case.

>From logs uploaded to SR# 693999363 we have identified 1 Cisco UCS M5 servers that are not configured to use a beneficial memory RAS feature called ADDDC Sparing.
ADDDC Sparing tracks correctable memory errors and dynamically maps out failing regions by putting those banks or ranks into virtual lockstep mode.
This can prevent correctable errors from accumulating and becoming uncorrectable.
ADDDC Sparing is now the default Memory RAS configuration on Cisco UCS M5 servers with Intel Xeon Scalable processors.
Cisco recommends that all Cisco UCS M5 servers enable this feature.
Please refer to the two links below for more information about this feature.
Cisco UCS M5 Memory Technical Overview - Memory RAS Features

FN - 70432 - Improved Memory RAS Features for UCS M5 Platforms - Software Upgrade Recommended

  2.  6. Click "Create Backup"

Based on your selections above, your backup schedule will begin on Sunday at 12:00 AM +8 and will continue weekly. All data, without Assurance data, will be saved.

  1.  Now we can see the correct time zone, fill other information and create the backup schedule.

Just wanted to follow up on our call.
I believe you were hitting CSCux53429 on your ASA which was causing the admin context to not create properly.
It is resolved in version 9.6.1, but if you were to upgrade your ASAs you'd also likely have to upgrade the 9300 chassis because as per the compatibility guide that version is only supported in FXOS 1.1.4:
http://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/security/asa/compatibility/asamatrx.html#pgfId-139390
However we were able to workaround it by reloading the ASA.
It's a condition that seems to be caused by creating and deletion of contexts, so it was likely triggered by something that was being configured today and I would not expect you to see the issue in production.
As discussed, I will proceed with the closure of this SR.

Usually it is indication of cables not connected properly (for example wrong ports connected), damaged cables or damaged hardware ports on modules.
I can see however, that those ports have links up, so it may be rather due to some problems with cables.
First I would like you to check stacking cables.
Pease unplug them and plug again, ensure that left port on upper device is connected with left port on lower (cables cannot be crossed between ports)
Second, I would like to do a cold boot of the devices.
Meaning we need to shut it down, unplug power cables for about 5mins, and then start it again.
In order to do so, you will need to schedule maintenance window, since traffic disruptions will occur during this process.
I can see that your device is running in hardware bypass, meaning that traffic is going through without inspection.
After reboot, you will need to enable this bypass again by issuing command on primary device:
> configure bypass open s1p1
> configure bypass open s2p1

As discussed on call, here is the explanation for would have dropped messages.
When there is an intrusion event showing “would have dropped”, it means the packet was passed already (was not dropped) before snort could determine that the packet matches to a rule which is configured to drop.
Now there can be multiple reasons for this behaviour.
As you have mentioned this is only happening on standby sensor, it could be due asymmetric routing as well.
There are three likely causes for this behaviour.
Cause 1
When snort receives a new stream of traffic it will put packets from that stream into a queue (buffer).
The packets in this queue will not be flushed to detection until one of a few things happens.
The most common occurances (but not all) of these things are:
-Snort sees enough data in the stream to determine the protocol(s) (or service(s)) in that stream.
This is called protocol aware flushing (PAF).
-Snort sees the end of the stream (snort must see both the client and the server end the connection).
-Snort does not see any additional packets from that stream for 180 seconds (this is the default timeout and can be configured in the stream 5 preprocessor settings).
Before the stream is flushed to detection (while the queue is being built), snort will send the packets in the stream on the wire (so it does not delay the traffic and inject latency).
Once the stream has been flushed to detection it will go through the rule evaluation.
All of the packets that have already been passed on the wire (packets in the queue) for the stream are evaluated at this time.
If any of the packets match a rule that is set to drop, snort will not be able to drop these packets as they have already been sent on the wire.
Cause 2
If a device is under heavy load, or the latency packet handling preprocessor is kicking in often, it can also cause this behavior.
If inline normalization is enabled and you are still seeing this behavior, the next likely cause is the latency handling packet preprocessor.
In certain cases, if a packet matches a rule that is set to drop, but that packet crossed the latency packet threshold, it's possible that the packet was fast-pathed before it could be dropped.
Why this happens depends on when the check is done for the packet time, and when the rule triggered.
Cause 3
Traffic passing through the sensor twice.(two different inline sets)
There are chances that when traffic is passing through sensor twice, it trigger rule with "Would have dropped".
For example, a 5 packet HTTP GET request whose first packet triggers a rule is blocked the first time through the sensor, only last packet will be dropped.
The second time through the sensor, it will see only 4 packets.
The connection got dropped, but when it finally flushes the partial get request because it is pruning the session, it will trigger the same rule with "Would have dropped" as the inline result.
Either ways, I would suggest following steps to troubleshoot more on this.
Enable inline normalization from NAP (Network analysis policy).
If you are using balance security and connectivity, please create a new NAP policy with base as “balance security and connectivity” and then enable Inline normalization.
More details about normalization.
http://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/firesight-management-center/117927-technote-firesight-00.html
If inline normalization is enabled and this is still happening, then it's likely ppm causing the packet to be fast-pathed before it can be dropped.
In order to determine if this is happening, you have the following options:
Enable rule 134:3.
Enabling this rule will generate an event each time a packet has been fast-pathed due to reaching the threshold set in the latency packet handling preprocessor.
If you enable this rule, and see another event with no inline result or "would have dropped" and you see an event for rule 134:3 at this same time, it's very likely that ppm is causing this.
Let me know if you have any questions.

Sorry for the late response.
I am afraid that there is no direct way to achieve what you would like to do.
However, I would like to tell you about existing possibilities.
There are two worth mentioning:
1.
You can configure thresholding for your Intrusion rules, so an event will be generated only after some rule fires enough times (defined by your threshold) during a period of time (also defined).
If you configure it this way along with email alerts, you will receive an alert only if the conditions were met (eg.
if you configure a threshold for a rule to generate an event after 10 hits, you will receive an email only after the rule fires 10 times).
The caveat here is that thresholding cannot be limited to email alerts only, so it will also work for your dashboard and every other logging destination.
Also, there is no option to configure it for file events.
2.
The second option is to configure a correlation policy.
It can give you a possibility to generate a notification whenever there will be a specific Intrusion or Malware event, however it does not provide you a direct way to count these events.
For Intrusion events, you can count connections during which those events occurred.
This feature is called a 'connection tracker'.
The correlation policy is a very powerful tool in general, however it may require a lot of time to configure it and adjust to your needs.
Below you can find links to the documentation, so you can review these options that I just mentioned.
Tuning Intrusion Policies with Thresholding:
http://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/security/firepower/610/configuration/guide/fpmc-config-guide-v61/tuning_intrusion_policies_using_rules.html#ID-2237-000006c6
External Alerting with Alert Responses:
www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/security/firepower/610/configuration/guide/fpmc-config-guide-v61/external_alerting_with_alert_responses.html
Working with Correlation Policies:
http://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/security/firepower/610/configuration/guide/fpmc-config-guide-v61/correlation_policies.html

Roughly 60% of ICMP traffic through the box is dropped with following trace output:

Type: CONN-SETTINGS
Subtype:
Result: DROP
Config:
class-map any-tcp
 match any
policy-map global_policy
 class any-tcp
  set connection conn-max 0 embryonic-conn-max 0 random-sequence-number disable
service-policy global_policy global

The class-map being matched is intended to match only TCP traffic, but in reality it has a "match any" statement, so ICMP traffic is being caught in it, and my suspicion is that some kind of buffer limit is being hit.

I initially advised that we would want to configure an ACL for "permit tcp any any" to match only TCP traffic and replace the class-map's match action with that one. However, I also found CSCvc79371, which was actually filed against this same hardware in another of this customer's SRs (680444855). Suspecting that the behavior might be caused by the bug, I had them clear xlates. This alleviated the issue only temporarily, and not completely (there was still considerable packet loss even after xlates were cleared on the primary).

We then failed over to the secondary unit and cleared xlates on all contexts, and after we did so, we did not observe any additional packet loss.

However, there is still a notable difference between nat pool and xlate allocations on the pri and sec boxes; the Active unit always shows more conns allocated than the Standby unit does, which indicates to me that the issue is at least partially caused by CSCvc79371.

I also noticed a large number of LU Allocate Failures (%ASA-3-210005) for TCP and UDP traffic on the Standby after the failover, which makes me think that perhaps there's a problem with memory. Utilization on the Pri/Stby is listed at 127% (a cosmetic bug), though block usage for 9344 was depleted at some point, so it may be a memory allocation problem on the Primary.

Problem Description :

** there is a script configured on the server which queries different external DNS server for the configured list of domain name at interval of 10 sec for 120 sec
** we found that after 60 sec, the server queries for 2K domain ( not for 10K domain)
** as discussed this change is not due to firepower, as firepower won't be able to stop the server form querying domain name to external DNS server

Problem Details: Policy deployment failed on one of the sensor. Policy deployment failed on one of the sensor.
Closed with Customer Permission

*   Policy deployment was failing on one stack.
  *   Looking into logs, we verified thet VDB version was not matching on both the devices in the stack.
  *   Looking into both devices’s ngfw.rules, they both were on same VDB however the vdb.conf file was not same.
  *   This can be due to vdb rollback or VDB update attempt, which wasn’t successful in the past.
  *   I changed the VDB version on secondary box on stack and tried. However it was still failing
  *   After we started ActionQueueScrape, the issue disappeared and we were able to deploy policy.

CASE SUMMARY:
Problem description:
-          Enabled IGMP querier on vlan interface on ASA on Firepower 9300.
Action taken:
-          Informed the below
IGMP Snooping Querier is a concept specific to a device that connects several multicast senders and receivers at Layer 2 with no multicast routing involved.
In other words, it would only be applicable
to a switch.
Since ASA is a firewall that always relies on PIM to route multicast traffic, IGMP Snooping in general and Snooping Querier designation in particular are not applicable to it.

Problem Details: Intermittent dropping the traffic by the P2P DENY policy as it is identifying the application as BitTorrent Intermittent dropping the traffic by the P2P DENY policy as it is identifying the application as BitTorrent timestamp : 2019-04-11T07:22:41.000+0000 || updatedby : raghukul || type : RESOLUTION SUMMARY || visibility : Internal || details : Issue 1: Mirror.nus.edu.org getting classified as BitTorrent
=============================================

he website  http://mirror.nus.edu.org though it is classified as Educational Institution, the content hosted on this site is basically firmware’s which are Linux variants.
++ When the user selects on the sub-directories there is an option to download the firmware with one of the below choices:

[cid:image001.png@01D3F1AD.612383B0]

++ Now, at this point if the user selects any option apart from the “torrent” download option, the rule evaluation works correctly and the application is not detected as P2P (BitTorrent) which is expected. The device treats this connection as a normal HTTP download.

++ However, if the user at this point selects the “torrent” download option which is the 5th entry in the image above. The download is initiated via the torrent client because the file is a torrent download.
++ The connection event at this point on the device are as shown below. This is where we detect the application as BitTorrent and this is the expected behavior.


Issue 2: Tag-Based versus Category based App Detectors:
==============================================

++ When we initiated the connection, we observed that the application protocol was detected as “HTTP” and the Web application was detected as “Web Browsing” for all the working and non-working scenario.
++ However, what is crucial is the “Client” field which was getting detected as BitTorrent and for that connection which was not getting blocked the “Client” field was rightly getting detected as “Browsers” (Chrome/Opera/Firefox).

++ The important factor to determine is how we decide on the “Client Field”. This field looks into the tags associated with the application detector and then based on that it determines the client in addition to looking at the user agent field.
++ In the past, we had seen false positive in client field detection when tags are used as part of the app detection. I was able to recreate the behavior associated with SSL and HTTPS traffic.

++ The rule that is configured to block BitTorrent is based on “Category” and “Tags”.
++ When it comes to app-detection and tags being used as criteria, it will not be precise as we are not really looking into the content that is being downloaded. Hence in your case, we observed that the connection even to the home page was being detected as a client with BitTorrent.

What do we do to avoid these false positives?
=====================================

++ The rule created to block the BitTorrent App needs to be configured based on Application Filter.
++ We need to get away with the Tag-based detection to make it more efficient and avoid the false positives.


Issue 3: Increasing the aggressiveness associated with BitTorrent:
===================================================

Increasing BitTorrent Detection Aggressiveness
----------------------------------------------------------------
We enhanced the system to share more information about specific flows throughout the system that can assist on the identification of a BitTorrent host, with the use of some specific aggressiveness settings we have allowed customers to add.

•    These settings can be added by editing the /var/sf/userappid.conf file in the FMC CLI and then doing a Policy Deploy to send all these configurations to the devices which are registered to the FMC.
•    These settings are NOT enabled by default to avoid any potential false positive issues that may occur in the system.
•    These capabilities are created by flagging specific hosts, or servers on a host as BitTorrent whenever we are not able to identify its traffic through any of our regular application detection algorithms. In other words, these capabilities only get triggered when the traffic we see is Unknown.

-Below is the configuration line needed to be add in /var/sf/userappid.conf :

appid<tab>bittorrent_aggressiveness<tab>80
•    Where <tab> is the actual tab space. It is very important to make sure that Tabs are added there instead of spaces, sometimes vi can mask a tab with a space so make sure that we are truly using tabs when we are adding these configurations.

-As described earlier, after doing this change in FMC, the policy has to be deployed again to the managed/concerned devices ( edit any rule in the access control policy, click on any of the tab in the rule e.g. application then click on save and you will get the option to deploy the same policy to the concerned devices )

+ And one more important thing we noticed from the attached syslogs is that there is only a single IP address ( 172.27.225.212 ) in all the 4 events of application getting allowed thus please fetch a report on historic data from syslog server ( application : BitTorrent, action : allow ) and analyze the output to make sure the IP address which are having these allow action to have further check on the machines.

+ In addition of this, please share the +,- 5 minutes logs from the time of occurrence of the concerned event i.e. Oct  9 03:59:52 , +,-5 mins and Oct  9 03:05:18 +,-5 mins to do further analysis.


Issue 4: After the upgrade, there was misclassification of VPN Client and AV Agent
================================================================

++ Issue was caused due to a bad app detector.
++ Raised a new defect with the engineering team.
++ Upgrade on the VDB solved the concern


Coming to the testing related to P2P and torrent blocking, here is what I used in the lab and was able to block all torrent traffic in the lab scenario:


  1.  Created a rule with the URL block with category highlighted as P2P (peer to peer)
     *   This category includes most of the torrent hosting websites.
     *   Advantage: We block known bad right upfront without putting load on snort to determine the applications.
  2.  Created a rule with app detector as p2p category
     *   This will address the concerns related to sites which are regular websites but support download of content via the torrent application.
     *   This rule is already configured in your case and we do not need any change for this.

Note: The URL rule created based on category should be placed above the app based rule. Logging to enabled only at the start of the connection.

Analysis Done:
============


  1.  Whenever we have application detection configured, the device needs some packets to identify what the application is.
  2.  Now, when we looked at the connection events on the FMC, we saw that the count for initiator and responder packets is non-zero (which is expected) also the bytes transferred under initiator and responder bytes was non-zero (again this is expected).
  3.  After this, we determine the application is torrent and then block the connection.
  4.  However, in the meantime the upstream device sees first few packets. In our case from the logs shared on the ASA we can see these connections having few bytes transferred.

This is expected behaviour and does not mean that torrent is not getting blocked.

Follow up questions for BitSight on report regeneration and addition details:


  1.  Can we have the amount of data transferred in the connection which is marked by them as torrent?
  2.  Additionally is it possible to provide details on the URL being referenced while the data is being downloaded?

Following is our understanding from the data available:
Following logs messages were recorded for the line card crash that occurred :

May 27 08:46:32: %SNMP-SW1-3-RESPONSE_DELAYED: processing GetNext of ipMRouteEntry.6.239.193.240.21.172.18.240.21.255.255.255.255 (21992 msecs)

May 27 08:46:45: %SNMP-SW1-3-RESPONSE_DELAYED: processing GetNext of ciscoIpMRouteEntry.14.239.192.4.189.0.0.0.0.255.255.255.255 (2252 msecs)
May 27 08:46:45: %OIR-SW1-6-INSREM: Switch 2 Physical Slot 1 - Module Type LINE_CARD  removed
May 27 08:46:45: %OIR-SW1-6-INSREM: Switch 2 Physical Slot 1 - Module Type LINE_CARD  inserted
As seen above in the log pattern, CPU MONITOR is the KEEP ALIVE messages which is exchanged between the supervisor and the line card every 30 seconds.
If 6 continuous heartbeat messages are missed, the supervisor will force reload the line card at the end of the 6th heartbeat miss.
In such situations the crashinfo generated for the line card reload event gives the details of crash and list of stacks called prior crash.
However in our case the crashinfo file is generated with file size zero and hence we have no information on the root cause/trigger for crash.
From the following  LC monitor dump files  shared on the case we understand that there is a high CPU on the device post line card reload.
The high CPU was recorded due to processes like "fw_lcp process", "Earl TML dfc blo" and "Lif main process".
Below is an explanation on what these processes are and why they consume more CPU resource under certain circumstances:
20180626-231751943_lc_monitor_dump_20180527-004902
20180626-231751942_lc_monitor_dump_20180527-005023
20180626-231751940_lc_monitor_dump_20180527-004904
20180626-231751941_lc_monitor_dump_20180527-005021
"Lif stats hw rea" and "fw_lcp process" have been seen in elevated levels on distributed linecards since at least early SXI releases according to my research.
There have been a number of bugs filed, that have in turn been closed because of the way the code functions.
Development has determined that if they try to reduce the amount of programming in these processes to try and lower the CPU utilization, then they run the risk of causing a larger service impact to the module/system because required processing is not happening in a timely manner.
EARL TML dfc blob is the process for EARL Transport management Library which will be used for transfer the EARL related tables, L2 Vlan database , L2 LIF, L2 PORT-Database, L2 shadow table, per vlan datastructures will be sent from the active supervisor to the new line card which is coming up.
Whenever new DFC line card comes up, first notification will be given to active supervisor and supervisor will start batching the list of tables and databases to linecard using ICC mechanism and Linecard will start receiving and downloading them into the Linecard memory and this will be required as part of the boot-up sequence of the Linecard.
These monitor file can be created when there is a high cpu utilization of LC which is usually happened when the LC is booted up.
If we refer to what the "Earl TML dfc blo" is responsible for,  the "lc_monitor_dump" is most likely created when the device boots up.
To summarize the above explanation- it is expected of the device to have high CPU immediately after a reboot or line card reload.
Due to lack of data generated during the time of issue (no corefile/ crashinfo with size 0 bytes) it would be difficult to speculate the possible cause of this issue.
Please let us know the following :
Ø  Is this is a repeated behavior on that specific line card or this is the first time the issue is seen for this line card
Ø  Do we have any monitoring device that can help us with possible CPU/memory utilization and user traffic pattern just before line card crash
Ø  Has device displayed symptoms of instability on SUP or in any other than the line card C6800-32P10G-XL
Based on our understanding for above queries we can suggest on the next course of action on this case.
Please let me know if you have any queries related to analysis shared above.

1.
Access UCSM.
2.
Go to [Chassis] > [Chassis 4] > [Servers] > [Server 2].
3.
On the right side of the screen, go to SEL Logs, then click on Clear Logs on the page.
[How to reset the memory errors counter]
You can reset the memory errors by SSH'ing into the UCSM and execute the below commands:
ca-1-A# scope server 4/2
ca-1-A /chassis/server # reset-all-memory-errors
ca-1-A /chassis/server* # commit

Thanks for your patience on this.
There is no specific (hard-set) limitation for the number of IP addresses that can be added to the SI Blacklist object.
Utilization of this feature is completely related to the CPU and Memory of the devices (FMC/FTD), and number of rules added on various policies as there is a wide variety of hardware models we sell.
Although, there is another option available as well for optimal device performance.
This option includes creating a network object group that includes all the IP addresses one would like to deny.
Then, in the access control policy a block rule is created with the aforementioned object.
Anytime one would like to deny more IP addresses, the new IP addresses would simply have to be added to the object.

Thanks for your time on the call today.
Running through the test today, it seems like we want to hold off on running the fix until next week.
As you requested, here's what we're going to do:
The suspected issue is CSCva57479 where the Root CA shows up in the trusted store, but the elasticsearch DB that runs context visibility isn't able to store the cert and fails trust.
The plan for our maintenance is to export the .pem of the root CA locally, go into the CLI root of the node, copy the exported cert into the filesystem, then add it to the file elasticsearch uses to store certs.
Once that file is appended with the root CA data, the context visibility page should start working again.
We also took a look at TCP dump filters to figure out how to filter by MAC address.
While the correct keywords are "ether host", it looks like the input validation will only allow lines with "ip host".
As a result, we made the rule
Ip host 1.1.1.1 or ether host aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:ff
Which will work because there is no 1.1.1.1 traffic and we fill the requirement of having "ip host" in the input.
Since it sounds like you want to set up the new call for the same general time, I'm happy to hold on this case and set this up with you when you're ready next time, just let me know what day and time you're shooting for.
If you have any more questions about the fix process or anything else, just let me know.

C6800(dscp-based Qos)<----------->N7K(dscp-cos mapping/ cos-based Qos)<----------->C6800(dscp-based Qos)

This is the Bug identified on your environment:
6.4.0.4 FMC WebUI cannot create a Series-3 stack
https://bst.cloudapps.cisco.com/bugsearch/bug/CSCvs23750
Symptom:
The FMC WebUI when running 6.4.0.4 through 6.4.0.6 software will not allow the creation of FP8100, FP8200 or FP8300 stack.
The FMC WebUI will incorrectly display the error message, "There are not enough available devices for a new stack".
Conditions:
Customer has upgraded their FMC to one of the versions specified above in the "Symptoms" section.
Workaround:
Downgrade the FMC to 6.4.0 to allow the creation of a FP8100, FP8200 and FP8300 stack.
We are basically seeing the same symptoms even after reimaging the Sensors and registering them to the FMC, they do not show as available devices to form a stack.
This issue has been identified to be on the FMC not the Firepower 8350 sensors.
BU Engineer suggested the downgrade option after a discussion with Developer Engineer tracking the defect.

Hope this email finds you well,
As you cans ee from the show module switch all we have that setup (quad-sup), so we will have one Active Chassis and One Standby chassis, the standby role will always be on the standby chassis, in this case if we never reload the Active supervisor (currently on chassis 1 slot 3) then the Standby role will always belong to the chassis 2.
Having said that, in order to mitigate the parity errors we can proceed as follows.
1.
Reload or reseat module 2 on switch 1, you can do it without causing any supervisor role change.
2.
Reload or reseat the module 3 on switch 2, then the supervisor on module 4 on switch 2 will take the Standby Hot role.
In the mean time the supervisor on module 3 on switch 2 will boot after some time as the CSSO.
3.
In order to recover the initial setup we need to perform a reload of the standby supervisor.
redundancy reload peer
After that we will have the module 3 on switch 2 as the Standby Hot and again module 4 on switch 2 as the CSSO.
Please let me know if it is clear for you, if so let me know how we can proceed with this service request.
Should you require any further assistance, please don't hesitate to contact me.

Thank you for the time on WebEx, please find below a summary of our
discussion below.
* DNA Center Assurance feature at this time is focused on high level
summary and to aid in troubleshooting ongoing network issues.
Hence detailed
historical event reports are not available to be exported from DNAC
currently.
* We are able to get an availability report, showing the percentage of
uptime of an Access Point, in a given time period.
* This feature is available starting DNAC 2.1.2.x.
* It can be accessed from the reports section under template "Network
Device Availability".
* We are able to get the most recent occurrence of when any AP went
down as a report.
* This feature is available in your current DNAC version.
* It can be accessed from the Assurance section > Network issues and
filtered using "AP down" or "AP flap" issue type.
* However, the availability trends over time are only available on the
DNAC GUI as a graph and is not exportable for executive review.
As
discussed, the event report from Prime Infrastructure is the feature that
can help out here.
Please let us know if you have any further questions on this matter.

The trigger for the memory leak here is the "SISF Main Thread" process, for which the tracebacks are coming up multiple times (documented in https://bst.cloudapps.cisco.com/bugsearch/bug/CSCvw22489<https://apc01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fbst.cloudapps.cisco.com%2Fbugsearch%2Fbug%2FCSCvw22489&data=05%7C01%7Cgeorgekingsley.paulsundararaj%40ncs.com.sg%7C924ed3eee36c4f01c52e08da41eb893f%7Cca90d8f589634b6ebca99ac468bcc7a8%7C1%7C0%7C637894777124956936%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=b2FXWfQIkrqmye73hZeU9a4Azb1kYQtHBIzYnl3QYXw%3D&reserved=0>).
The bug which documents this memory leak (https://bst.cloudapps.cisco.com/bugsearch/bug/CSCvv16874) also has IOS version 17.3.5 as a fixed release.
Therefore, the next action plan would be to perform an IOS upgrade in order to mitigate the issue.

More detailed information can be found in the original bug: https://bst.cloudapps.cisco.com/bugsearch/bug/CSCvu07084.

 * Informed you that we have discussed about your requirement with the development team and below is the solution provided by them . 
* ISE endpoint API to get all endpoints; has the option to filter; one of the filters is groupId. So, the customers may get the groupId using ISE endpointgroup API and then use that as the filter. 
* GET; /ers/config/endpoint; * ;
 * Get all endpoints Implementation Notes This API allows the client to get all the endpoints. Filter: Filters can be used to filter out Endpoints based on a set of attributes. This API currently provides the following filters: [logicalProfileName, portalUser, staticProfileAssignment, profileId, profile, groupId, staticGroupAssignment, mac] 
* You informed that you will try to implement the suggested solution and will get back to us if you have any queries regarding this .
* Got a confirmation from your side that the query fulfilled the requirement and we are good for the case closure .

Problem Details: Hi TAC team,

Our customer has logged a crash on their ASA FW and have sent over the crashinfo logs.

Kindly assist us in going through the logs and finding the cause of the crash

Thank you. Hi TAC team,

Our customer has logged a crash on their ASA FW and have sent over the crashinfo logs.

Kindly assist us in going through the logs and finding the cause of the crash

Thank you. Based on the show tech, I can see that CPU, memory are good. All the interfaces are up. All processes are running fine.
CPU utilization for 5 seconds = 15%; 1 minute: 12%; 5 minutes: 12%
Free memory:       11955556008 bytes (83%)
 
Your ASA doesn’t have coredump file ‘coredumpfsys’ in its flash.
 
After examining the crashinfo,  I understand your device running ASA 9.14(2)15 crashed on 2021-09-06 due to bug CSCvy48159 https://bst.cloudapps.cisco.com/bugsearch/bug/CSCvy48159  - ASA Traceback & reload on process name Lina due to memory header validation.
 
Workaround-
Disabling threat detection at the CLI will prevent this crash, but doing so may trigger a second crash (also covered under this defect ID). Therefore the following is recommended:

For Standalone setups:
> Save the config of the device (do not perform any further changes until all steps below described are followed)
> Retrieve startup config from affected device
> Remove "threat-detection" lines from retrieved file
> Upload new file to flash of device
> Copy the config from the file to the startup config: 
copy flash:/ startup-config
> Reload the device
 
Permanent fix-
You can upgrade the device to version 9.14.3 which is a known fixed release as per the bug page.
Closed

Problem Details: ISE 2.3  RADIUS Accounting - Interim update - Endpoint IP address and MAC address missing ISE 2.3  RADIUS Accounting - Interim update - Endpoint IP address and MAC address missing As discussed :


  1.  It is expected to see some Accounting Start packets not having an IP address as accounting start packets are sent as soon as the user is authenticated irrespective of whether or not the user got an IP address. It so can happen that the user may get an IP address after a second or so and not immediately after the authentication and in such cases, the accounting start may not have an IP address.
  2.  It sometimes can so happen that the interim updates may also miss an IP address. This happens when the DHCP lease time expires and the end device has to renew its lease or when the endpoint moves from one AP to another AP and mistakes it for a network change and refreshes IP etc.
  3.  Having said point number 2. Only one 2 such interim updates per user per endpoint can be expected. Eventually that user/endpoint should get an IP address and should be available in the subsequent interim updates. It cannot happen that such an endpoint doesn’t get an IP for the entire day if it still has an active session and connected to the network.

Also, Accounting is not a 100% full proof method to take any security measures in a network and one should not rely solely on that for the above mentioned reasons and also especially because of the fact that these syslogs are sent over an unsecure medium to start with and anyone can tamper with them. Anyways, that is for the customer to decide.

FS4000 CVE-2021-44228 - Zero-Day Vulnerability in Apache Java Logging Library Log4j
FS4000 Discussed over the call few packets are allowed on the firewall to determine the packet.

Sharing the below document for the same.

https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/firepower-ngfw/212321-clarify-the-firepower-threat-defense-acc.html

Note: In order for the Snort engine to determine the application it has to inspect a few packets (usually 3-10 which depends on the application decoder). Thus a few packets are allowed through the FTD and they make it to the destination. The allowed packets are still subject to the Intrusion Policy check based on the Access Policy > Advanced >  'Intrusion Policy used before Access Control rule is determined' option.



Every intrusion event which is generated on the device is because of the content match which is mentioned in the SID.

The last log observed from the support bundle was from 2019-04-26 23:59:48. Around this time we can observe only 1 node has come up, and in total 11 are Live nodes out of the 15 nodes in deployment. More so , we can see HSDC-EDU-NAC-01 came alive, and started responding to it and hence for this node, the replication as in progress. However as mentioned before, since the debugs and the exact timestamp is not known, we cannot determine the trigger here which caused them to fall out of sync and eventually mark them as dead on the PAN node.

At this point after exhausting all the resources, I believe something in the network might have blocked the communication between the nodes, or a firewall might have blocked communication, or it could be any other trigger causing the communication between the PAN and these affected nodes to fail, due to which PAN might have marked them as dead. But since debugs were not enabled and we aren’t aware of the of the exact timestamp, we cannot determine the root cause or the trigger.

Going forward, I would suggest you to make sure that nothing in your network ( ex- firewall, network slowness etc) might be interfering between internode communications. Since these nodes might be at different sites, it is highly probable that something in your network might have blocked the internode communication.

However, if this is a frequent issue, we can discuss the possibility of enabling the debugs on ISE, which would help us capture the root trigger, in case the issue happens again.

Resolution Summary:


++ Log analysis for the replication issue was done and you were informed of the findings.

++ informed about how to configure alarms.
ISE node replication stopped due to which few of the nodes fell out of sync.

Problem Details: We want to monitor the radar detection in our WLAN. Can we get these logs from the WLC? Specifically when an AP resets its channel because of a radar. Thanks We want to monitor the radar detection in our WLAN. Can we get these logs from the WLC? Specifically when an AP resets its channel because of a radar. Thanks - As discussed, you can check Radar detection from AP side. Also, we can check the Radar activity from WLC by checking traplog.
- Confirmed that it is possible to send AP logs to a configured syslog server with two conditions as follows:
1-  Since DFS message has the informational level "6", the syslog level on the WLC configuration for syslog server should be informational and not any less level 
2- In addition, we should configure it Globally or by specific AP using the below commands:
Globally: config ap syslog host global <syslog IP >
Specific AP: config ap syslog host specific <ap name> <ip address>

- Then, you can check the configuration before and after issuing the command by using the following show command:
WLC> show ap config global

-   As per our discussion, the only way to send the radar logs for the syslog server is to configure the mentioned commands. Since it will cause heavy load on syslog server, you can open enhancement request which would be evaluated by BU to allow the possibility for enabling/ disabling the messages in msglogs like the traps.

- Since all of your concerns are clear now, you've requested to close the case as no further assistance is needed.

Problem Description: 
- DNAC Wireless Assurance health score shows 0 after May 15 9:00 PM SGT.
- Issue seen after provisioning the WLC.
- **Provisioning time:** May 15 @ 12:53 UTC.

Setup Info:
- DNAC version: 2.3.3.7
- WLC we are focusing:
    - **Hostname:** TLDC-WL-WLC01
    - **IP:** 172.18.240.13
    - **HW/SW:** AIR-CT8540-K9 / 8.10.183.0

Tshoot/Analysis:
-	We have seen that Wireless assurance is missing in DNAC since around May 15 9:00 PM SGT.
-	Checking WLC configuration we see that it is disabled.
-	Checking DNAC site settings we see that Wireless telemetry is disabled.
-	We also observed that around 8:53 PM SGT, the WLC was provisioned as part of another activity.
-	Suspect that the WLC was provisioned with Wireless telemetry disabled as per the site settings configured in DNAC.
-	However, the audit log details, or configuration preview do not indicate that wireless assurance was disabled.
-	You forced pushed the telemetry settings to WLC [172.18.240.13]  during MW on 20 May. However that does not seem to enable the WSA service on the WLC.
-	On further analysis, identified following defects which have been root caused to CSCvk62901 libssh2 library upgrade for WLC 
CSCvq42714 WLC WSA service is disabled after discovery and provisioning due to which it says unmonitored
CSCvp20941 Assurance configs are not getting pushed to WLC.
-	engaged Sudhanshu from WLC team who validated this in lab and it was working as expected.
-	In order to further isolate the issue and he requested following details.
o	Save the putty session of WLC and run the below debugs on WLC.
show logging config-history
debug emweb web enable
debug pm pki enable
o	Trigger the issue by doing 'Update Telemetry Settings' --> "Force Configuration push" from DNAC.
o	  After running the above debugs commands on WLC and triggering the issue from DNAC, wait for 10 min to collect the outputs on WLC, then close the SSH session and share the file.
o	  From DNAC side, upload the RCA file.

-	As per your last update,
Telemetry Settings for wlc01 had been updated on 4th of July and assurance got enabled for that WLC since then.
-	As per your request we monitored the status by end of the week and did not receive any further issues reported.
